{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"01e96ba2-df8a-4350-828f-797540ae7698","content":"No project found at that path, but here's the configuration you need.\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for MCP).\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout**. Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n\nIf you've already published the server as a standalone executable, you can point directly to it instead:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot Chat panel in agent mode — VS Code will detect and start the server automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"09d4d7d6-cdf8-4fc1-8d39-7d325f7119e1","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"F05A:F615C:123498E:148F40B:69F940ED"},"id":"c2c4fa33-3771-42f2-9d7f-edca35d4f7bc","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:59:33.495Z","parentId":"08a9de15-af08-4f31-8b84-c96c90b04e7c"}
